<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-533-790  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 533 790.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  June 12 1990 v4 n22 p1(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Apple CD drive back-ordered: price cut, developer discs spurdemand. (Apple Computer Inc.'s AppleCD SC CD-ROM disk drive)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cohen, Raines.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (products).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Product:   Apple AppleCD SC (CD-ROM drive) (marketing).andO;Topic:     CD-ROMDisk DrivesMarketing StrategyDemandPrice Cutting.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Price cut, developer discs spur demandandM;By Raines CohenandM;Cupertino, Calif.andP;  -- Apple's AppleCD SC CD-ROM drive, until recently a slowseller, is back-ordered up to two months.andM;February's price cut of 25 percent, which lowered the drive's retail pricefrom $1,199 to $899, succeeded beyond Apple's expectations in spurring sales,a company spokeswoman said.andM;But industry observers said demand is still coming primarily from developersrather than end users.andP;  Apple, which reiterated its &quot;aggressive commitment tothis technology&quot; when it announced the price cut, is increasinglydistributing developer tools, system software and technical information onCD-ROM discs.andM;Attendees at Apple's Worldwide Developers Conference last month receivedprerelease copies of System 7.0 on CD-ROM as part of the conference fee buthad to pay $100 for the same material on floppy disk and paper.andM;The Apple strategy, however, has left some developers stewing over theshortage.andP;  &quot;It's kind of ridiculous that Apple gives us all this great stuffon CD-ROM, but then tells us we have to wait until September to get a drivewe order today,&quot; one developer said.andM;Dealers contacted by MacWEEK said third-party drives are selling well tocustomers unwilling to wait for Apple's.andP;  &quot;Our Porta-Drives [from CDTechnology Inc. of San Jose, Calif.] have been flying out the door ever sincethe developers conference.andP;  They've hit every [Apple] dealer in the area andare looking for alternatives,&quot; said Yugi Honma, manager of ComputerWare inPalo Alto, Calif.andM;Other factors contributing to the new interest in the optical medium include:andM;andgt;Corporate usage.andP;  Companies reportedly are discovering that in-houseinformation can be distributed economically on CD-ROM.andP;  &quot;Most of our [CD-ROMdrive] business lately has been large purchases from companies distributinginformation internally on CD-ROM,&quot; said William Liu, president of CDTechnology.andM;andgt;More titles.andP;  While the much-touted Lotus MarketPlace has yet to ship, thelist of available CD-ROMs has slowly grown.andP;  Particularly popular, dealerssaid, are two recent multimedia titles, Warner New Media's The Magic Fluteand The Voyager Co.'s Ludwig van Beethoven: Symphony No.andP;  9 CD Companion.andO;Apple's new Technical Information Source CD-ROM also is selling well, theysaid.andM;andgt;Apple promotions.andP;  Apple gave away sampler discs through a promotion withMacUser magazine that started in March, and many users just now receiving thefree discs have begun shopping for a way to use them.andO;</TEXT></DOC>